### §4.1 Three named pathways

> **HP capacity rationale.** The screen's 1,287 kW "average demand" figure is an *all-end-uses* number (steam + hot water averaged over operating hours). The optimiser sizes the mid-temperature HP against the **hot-water sub-demand only** — the steam header (175°C) is out of single-stage NH3 envelope and stays on retained gas + EB. Hot-water at 7 GWh/yr over 5,440 op hours averages ~1,290 kW, but the cleaning-in-place pulse profile drops the steady-state load well below average; an `hp_mid_1000` (1,000 kW) covers the median draw with the EB / gas backstop catching peaks. Up-sizing to `hp_mid_2000` (Aggressive) buys the peak hours but only by paying double capex for incremental hot-water displacement — the NPV-vs-carbon Pareto in §4.2 makes the trade-off explicit.


